      <div
        class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tight prose-a:text-brand-600"
      >
        <h2>Common takeoff mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Scaling from a PDF.</strong> PDFs resize when displayed or printed and frequently
            don't reflect the stated plan scale. Always use the dimension strings on the drawing. If you're
            using on-screen takeoff tools, calibrate against a verified dimension before measuring.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Missing an addendum.</strong> Addenda during the bidding period regularly change scope,
            material specs, or design details. Pricing the original drawings after an addendum has superseded
            them means you're bidding a different job than the GC expects.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Not reading the spec.</strong> The drawings show locations and layouts; the specs
            define what gets installed there. Bidding the drawings without reading your division's spec
            section is a reliable way to price the wrong material.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>One waste factor for everything.</strong> A flat waste percentage across all materials
            and conditions underestimates some items and overestimates others. Per-material and per-condition
            factors, drawn from actual job history, are more accurate.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Skipping the site visit.</strong> Plans can't show existing conditions — underground
            obstructions, low structural clearances, restricted access points, or work already in place.
            A site walk before bid day catches things that would change your labor estimate if you found
            them on day one.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>No independent check on the counts.</strong> Running the count on one area twice,
            or having a second estimator spot-check a few key items, catches transposition errors and
            unit mismatches before they carry into pricing.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Pricing the work after the takeoff</h2>
        <p>
          Once you have verified quantities, the estimate applies costs: material pricing from
          current supplier quotes, labor hours from your production rates, equipment, sub-tier, and
          then markup for overhead and profit. The takeoff and the estimate are two distinct steps
          because they require different information — one reads drawings, the other prices to
          market conditions and your own cost structure.
        </p>
        <p>
          Understanding <a href="/blog/construction-markup-vs-margin/"
            >how markup and margin interact</a
          > matters at this stage. Markup is a percentage added to cost; margin is the profit percentage
          of the final price. They describe the same dollars from different directions, and the percentages
          are never equal — many subs price to a markup number when they intend a specific margin, and
          the gap costs real money across a year of bids.
        </p>
        <p>
          <a href="/features/construction-bidding/">BuildWorkPro's bidding tools</a> apply margin and
          overhead from the Rates tab across all line items, so the math is consistent from one bid to
          the next — no per-line markup juggling and no chance of applying different rates to different
          sections of the estimate.
        </p>
      </div>

